Let G be the standard generator matrix:

G := \begin{pmatrix}
1 & 0 & 0 & 0 & 1 \\
0 & 1 & 0 & 1 & 0 \\
0 & 0 & 1 & 1 & 1 \end{pmatrix}

G generates the linear code C:

C = \{00000, 00111, 01010, 01101, 10001, 10110, 11011, 11100\}

The minimum distance of C is 3, allowing it to detect 1 transmission error and correct 0 transmission errors.

Multiplying G by the vectors 000, 001, 010, 011, 100, 101, 110, 111 gives:

1. \begin{pmatrix} 0 & 0 & 0 \end{pmatrix} G = \begin{pmatrix} 0 & 0 & 0 & 0 & 0 \end{pmatrix}
2. \begin{pmatrix} 0 & 0 & 1 \end{pmatrix} G = \begin{pmatrix} 0 & 0 & 1 & 1 & 1 \end{pmatrix}
3. \begin{pmatrix} 0 & 1 & 0 \end{pmatrix} G = \begin{pmatrix} 0 & 1 & 0 & 1 & 0 \end{pmatrix}
4. \begin{pmatrix} 0 & 1 & 1 \end{pmatrix} G = \begin{pmatrix} 0 & 1 & 1 & 0 & 1 \end{pmatrix}
5. \begin{pmatrix} 1 & 0 & 0 \end{pmatrix} G = \begin{pmatrix} 1 & 0 & 0 & 0 & 1 \end{pmatrix}
6. \begin{pmatrix} 1 & 0 & 1 \end{pmatrix} G = \begin{pmatrix} 1 & 0 & 1 & 1 & 0 \end{pmatrix}
7. \begin{pmatrix} 1 & 1 & 0 \end{pmatrix} G = \begin{pmatrix} 1 & 1 & 0 & 1 & 1 \end{pmatrix}
8. \begin{pmatrix} 1 & 1 & 1 \end{pmatrix} G = \begin{pmatrix} 1 & 1 & 1 & 0 & 0 \end{pmatrix}

All arithmetic is modulo 2.

2 codewords have weight 2, and 5 have weight 3. The minimum distance of C is 2. C can detect 3 - 1 = 0 transmission errors and correct \lfloor \frac{2 - 1}{2} \rfloor = 0 transmission errors.

